        </image>
    </figure>

    <example>
        <title>Volume Change Under a Linear Map</title>
        <p>
            In engineering applications, matrices often represent linear transformations of space. If a matrix <m>A</m> maps the unit cube to a parallelepiped, then the factor by which volumes are scaled is <m>\lvert\det(A)\rvert</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            For example, if <m>\det(A)=2</m>, then every small volume element is doubled. If <m>\det(A)=-2</m>, then the volume is still doubled, but the orientation is reversed.
        </p>
    </example>

    <p>
        In dimensions <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>, the determinant can still be written down by explicit formulas. Beginning with dimension <m>4</m>, however, these formulas become so complicated that they are of little conceptual value. Rather than studying such formulas in general, we take a different point of view: we use the following theorem as the definition of the determinant in arbitrary dimension. It asserts that for every <m>n\in\mathbb{N}</m>, there exists a unique map on <m>n\times n</m>-matrices satisfying the fundamental properties that a determinant should have.
    </p>

    <theorem>
        <title>Axiomatic Definition of the Determinant</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                For every <m>n\in\mathbb{N}</m>, there exists a unique map
                <me>
                    \det:\mathbb{R}^{n\times n}\to\mathbb{R}
                </me>
                with the following properties.
            </p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The determinant is <term>multilinear</term>, that is, it is compatible with sums and scalar multiplication in each column.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The determinant is <term>alternating</term>, that is, interchanging two columns changes the sign.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The determinant is normalized by
                        <me>
                            \det(I_n)=1.
                        </me>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
        Beyond theoretically guaranteeing the existence of determinants for matrices of dimension 4 or higher, this theorem also gives us more information on the behaviour of the determinant in small dimensions:
    </p>

    <example>
        <title>Scaling a Matrix</title>
        <p>
            Let <m>A</m> be a <m>3\times 3</m>-matrix with <m>\det(A)=4</m>. We determine <m>\det(3A)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            If the columns of <m>A</m> are <m>\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{w}</m>, then the columns of <m>3A</m> are <m>3\mathbf{u},3\mathbf{v},3\mathbf{w}</m>. By multilinearity,
            <me>
                \det(3A)=\det(3\mathbf{u},3\mathbf{v},3\mathbf{w})=3^3\det(\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{w})=27\det(A).
            </me>
            Therefore
            <me>
                \det(3A)=27\cdot 4=108.
            </me>
        </p>
    </example>

    <p>
        While determinants are cumbersome to compute in general, certain calculation rules make the computation easier in some situations:
    </p>

    <theorem>
        <title>Calculation Rules for Determinants</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be <m>n\times n</m>-matrices.
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The determinant is multiplicative:
                        <me>
                            \det(AB)=\det(A)\det(B).
                        </me>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The determinant does not change under transposition:
                        <me>
                            \det(A^T)=\det(A).
                        </me>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If <m>A</m> is triangular, then its determinant is the product of the diagonal entries:
                        <me>
                            \det(A)=a_{11}\cdots a_{nn}.
                        </me>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
        These rules are very useful in practice. In particular, the formula for triangular matrices allows us to compute many determinants immediately.
    </p>

    <example>
        <title>Determinants of Triangular Matrices</title>
        <p>
            For
            <me>
                A=
                \begin{pmatrix}
                    1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3\\
                    0 &amp; 7 &amp; 1\\
                    0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
                \end{pmatrix}
            </me>
            we have
            <me>
                \det(A)=1\cdot 7\cdot 1=7.
            </me>
        </p>
        <p>
            For
            <me>
                B=
                \begin{pmatrix}
                    1 &amp; 0 &amp; 0\\
                    2 &amp; 8 &amp; 0\\
                    4 &amp; 5 &amp; 3
                \end{pmatrix}
            </me>
            we obtain
            <me>
                \det(B)=1\cdot 8\cdot 3=24.
            </me>
        </p>
    </example>

    <p>
        One has to be careful with sums of matrices. In general,
        <me>
            \det(A+B)\neq \det(A)+\det(B).
        </me>
        The determinant behaves well with respect to matrix multiplication, but not with respect to matrix addition.
    </p>

    <theorem>
        <title>Criteria for a Matrix to be Invertible</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>A</m> be an <m>n\times n</m>-matrix. Then the following statements are equivalent.
            </p>
            <ol>
                <li><p><m>A</m> is invertible.</p></li>
                <li><p>There exists an <m>n\times n</m>-matrix <m>B</m> with <m>AB=I_n</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>There exists an <m>n\times n</m>-matrix <m>B</m> with <m>BA=I_n</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p><m>A^T</m> is invertible.</p></li>
                <li><p>The columns of <m>A</m> are linearly independent.</p></li>
                <li><p><m>\operatorname{rank}(A)=n</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>The homogeneous linear system <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}</m> has only the trivial solution.</p></li>
                <li><p>For every <m>\mathbf{b}\in\mathbb{R}^n</m>, the linear system <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m> has a solution.</p></li>
                <li><p>For every <m>\mathbf{b}\in\mathbb{R}^n</m>, the linear system <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m> has a unique solution.</p></li>
                <li><p><m>\det(A)\neq 0</m>.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
        In particular, a square matrix is invertible exactly if its determinant is non-zero. This gives a simple numerical criterion for invertibility.
    </p>

    <example>
        <title>Solvability for Arbitrary Right-Hand Sides</title>
        <p>
            Consider
            <me>
                A=
                \begin{pmatrix}
                    1 &amp; 2 &amp; 0\\
                    a &amp; 1 &amp; 0\\
                    0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
                \end{pmatrix}.
            </me>
            We want to determine for which values of <m>a</m> the system
            <me>
                A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}
            </me>
            has a solution for every <m>\mathbf{b}\in\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            By the theorem above, this is equivalent to <m>A</m> being invertible, and hence equivalent to
            <me>
                \det(A)\neq 0.
            </me>
        </p>
        <p>
            We compute
            <me>
                \det(A)
                =
                1\cdot 1\cdot 1
                +2\cdot 0\cdot 0
                +0\cdot a\cdot 0
                -0\cdot 1\cdot 0
                -1\cdot 0\cdot 0
                -2\cdot a\cdot 1
                =
                1-2a.
            </me>
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore
            <me>
                \det(A)\neq 0
                \quad\Longleftrightarrow\quad
                1-2a\neq 0
                \quad\Longleftrightarrow\quad
                a\neq \frac12.
            </me>
            Hence the system <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m> has a solution for every right-hand side exactly for
            <me>
                a\neq \frac12.
            </me>
        </p>
    </example>

    <theorem>
        <title>Cramer's Rule for <m>2\times 2</m>-Matrices</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let
                <me>
                    A=
                    \begin{pmatrix}
                        a_{11} &amp; a_{12}\\
                        a_{21} &amp; a_{22}
                    \end{pmatrix}
                </me>
                be a <m>2\times 2</m>-matrix with <m>\det(A)\neq 0</m>, and let
                <me>
                    \mathbf{b}=
                    \begin{pmatrix}
                        b_1\\
                        b_2
                    \end{pmatrix}.
                </me>
                Then the unique solution of
                <me>
                    A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}
                </me>
                is given by
                <me>
                    \mathbf{x}=
                    \begin{pmatrix}
                        x_1\\
                        x_2
                    \end{pmatrix}
                </me>
                with
                <me>
                    x_1=
                    \frac{
                        \det\begin{pmatrix}
                            b_1 &amp; a_{12}\\
                            b_2 &amp; a_{22}
                        \end{pmatrix}
                    }{
                        \det\begin{pmatrix}
                            a_{11} &amp; a_{12}\\
                            a_{21} &amp; a_{22}
                        \end{pmatrix}
                    },
                    \qquad
                    x_2=
                    \frac{
                        \det\begin{pmatrix}
                            a_{11} &amp; b_1\\
                            a_{21} &amp; b_2
                        \end{pmatrix}
                    }{
                        \det\begin{pmatrix}
                            a_{11} &amp; a_{12}\\
                            a_{21} &amp; a_{22}
                        \end{pmatrix}
                    }.
                </me>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
        Cramer's rule gives an explicit solution formula for small systems. For larger systems, Gaussian elimination is usually more efficient.
    </p>

    <exercises>
        <title>Check Your Understanding</title>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let
                    <me>
                        A=
                        \begin{pmatrix}
                            4 &amp; 1\\
                            2 &amp; 3
                        \end{pmatrix}.
                    </me>
                    What is <m>\det(A)</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <choices>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>14</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. The determinant is not the sum of all entries.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice correct="yes">
                    <statement><p><m>10</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Correct. We have <m>\det(A)=4\cdot 3-1\cdot 2=12-2=10</m>.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>8</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. Use the rule main diagonal minus anti-diagonal.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>2</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. Recompute the two products carefully.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
            </choices>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let
                    <me>
                        A=
                        \begin{pmatrix}
                            1 &amp; 3\\
                            2 &amp; 1
                        \end{pmatrix}.
                    </me>
                    Which statement is true?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <choices>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>\det(A)=5</m> and the orientation is positive.</p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. The determinant is negative.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice correct="yes">
                    <statement><p><m>\det(A)=-5</m> and the area of the parallelogram is <m>5</m>.</p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Correct. The absolute value gives the area, while the sign gives the orientation.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>\det(A)=-5</m> and the area of the parallelogram is <m>-5</m>.</p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. An area is non-negative; the sign refers to orientation.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>\det(A)=1</m> and the area of the parallelogram is <m>1</m>.</p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. Compute the determinant directly.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
            </choices>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>A</m> be a <m>3\times 3</m>-matrix with <m>\det(A)=4</m>. What is <m>\det(3A)</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <choices>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>12</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. For a <m>3\times 3</m>-matrix, the determinant scales with the third power.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice correct="yes">
                    <statement><p><m>108</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Correct. We have <m>\det(3A)=3^3\det(A)=27\cdot 4=108</m>.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>36</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. The factor is <m>27</m>, not <m>9</m>.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p>It cannot be determined.</p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. The determinant rules give enough information.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
            </choices>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For which value of <m>a</m> is the matrix
                    <me>
                        \begin{pmatrix}
                            1 &amp; 2\\
                            a &amp; 4
                        \end{pmatrix}
                    </me>
                    not invertible?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <choices>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>a=1</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. Set the determinant equal to zero.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice correct="yes">
                    <statement><p><m>a=2</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Correct. We have <m>\det(A)=1\cdot 4-2a=4-2a</m>, so the determinant is zero exactly for <m>a=2</m>.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>a=4</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. Then the determinant is <m>-4</m>.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p>The matrix is invertible for every <m>a</m>.</p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. A square matrix is not invertible when its determinant is zero.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
            </choices>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let
                    <me>
                        A=
                        \begin{pmatrix}
                            2 &amp; -1 &amp; 3\\
                            0 &amp; 5 &amp; 4\\
                            0 &amp; 0 &amp; -2
                        \end{pmatrix}.
                    </me>
                    What is <m>\det(A)</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <choices>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>20</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. The matrix is triangular, so multiply all diagonal entries including the sign.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>-10</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. One diagonal factor is missing.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice correct="yes">
                    <statement><p><m>-20</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Correct. Since <m>A</m> is upper triangular, <m>\det(A)=2\cdot 5\cdot (-2)=-20</m>.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>0</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. A triangular matrix has determinant zero only if one diagonal entry is zero.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
            </choices>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>
</subsection>